WEBVTT

00:08.734 --> 00:10.401
Aren't the clouds
beautiful?

00:10.468 --> 00:12.633
They look like
big balls of cotton.

00:14.700 --> 00:17.034
I could just
lie here all day

00:17.101 --> 00:19.001
and watch them
drift by.

00:21.001 --> 00:22.967
If you use
your imagination,

00:23.034 --> 00:24.368
you could see
lots of things

00:24.434 --> 00:26.001
in the cloud
formations.

00:26.067 --> 00:28.401
What do you think
you see, Linus?

00:29.567 --> 00:31.800
Well, those clouds
up there look to me

00:31.867 --> 00:34.967
like the map of the british
honduras on the caribbean.

00:36.368 --> 00:37.934
That cloud up there

00:38.001 --> 00:41.301
looks a little like the
profile of thomas eakins,

00:41.368 --> 00:43.201
the famous painter
and sculptor.

00:43.267 --> 00:45.234
And that group of clouds
over there

00:45.301 --> 00:48.101
<i>gives me the impression
of the stoning of stephen.</i>

00:48.167 --> 00:49.967
I can see
the apostle paul

00:50.034 --> 00:52.001
standing there
to one side.

00:52.067 --> 00:54.234
Uh-huh.
That's very good.

00:54.301 --> 00:57.201
What do you see in the
clouds, Charlie Brown?

00:58.368 --> 00:59.500
Well,

00:59.567 --> 01:01.533
I was going to say
I saw a ducky

01:01.600 --> 01:04.233
and a horsy,
but I changed my mind.

02:09.201 --> 02:12.834
<i>like the shadows
of morning</i>

02:16.734 --> 02:21.468
<i>climb up
to the august afternoon</i>

02:24.301 --> 02:27.167
<i>Charlie has a way</i>

02:28.234 --> 02:31.101
<i>of picking up the day</i>

02:32.800 --> 02:37.334
<i>just by walking slowly
in a room</i>

02:40.633 --> 02:45.434
<i>maybe it's a kind of magic</i>

02:48.934 --> 02:53.368
<i>that only little boys
can do</i>

02:55.167 --> 02:59.301
<i>but seeing Charlie smile</i>

03:00.234 --> 03:04.667
<i>can make you stop awhile</i>

03:04.734 --> 03:08.633
<i>and get you feeling glad
you're you</i>

03:12.434 --> 03:17.134
<i>he's only a boy
named Charlie</i>

03:21.134 --> 03:25.800
<i>a boy named Charlie Brown</i>

03:28.567 --> 03:31.468
<i>he's just a kid next door</i>

03:31.533 --> 03:34.201
<i>perhaps a little more</i>

03:36.368 --> 03:41.301
<i>he's every kid
in every town</i>

03:44.734 --> 03:49.600
<i>the world is full
of lots of people</i>

03:52.434 --> 03:57.301
<i>here and there
and all around</i>

03:59.401 --> 04:04.201
<i>but people, after all</i>

04:04.267 --> 04:07.834
<i>start out as being small</i>

04:09.134 --> 04:12.967
<i>and we're all a boy named</i>

04:13.034 --> 04:16.733
<i>Charlie Brown</i>

05:34.301 --> 05:37.533
I'll never be able
to get this kite in the air.

05:37.600 --> 05:40.800
Never! Never!
Never! Never!

05:40.867 --> 05:44.434
I can't do it.
I can't do it.

05:46.067 --> 05:49.667
I don't want to see this
kite again as long as I live.

05:53.034 --> 05:56.633
Take it. Take it.
Get it out of my sight!

05:58.101 --> 06:01.368
Anybody who can fly this kite is a genius.

06:30.101 --> 06:31.633
<i>My heart is full</i>

06:31.700 --> 06:34.434
<i>on the day I first go out
to the old ball field.</i>

06:35.633 --> 06:37.900
<i>I love the memories.</i>

06:39.567 --> 06:42.468
<i>I love the smell
of the horsehide.</i>

06:44.267 --> 06:48.201
<i>I love the smell of the grassy
outfield and the dusty infield.</i>

06:50.167 --> 06:54.401
<i>The hopes and the dreams
for the new season.</i>

06:54.468 --> 06:57.567
<i>Ah, there it is,
the old pitcher's mound,</i>

06:57.633 --> 07:00.800
<i>covered with tradition
and dandelions.</i>

07:00.867 --> 07:02.267
<i>Dandelions?</i>

07:04.468 --> 07:07.301
This pitcher's mound
is covered with dandelions!

07:07.368 --> 07:10.234
Don't touch them,
Charlie Brown!

07:10.301 --> 07:13.533
Don't you dare hurt all
those innocent dandelions.

07:14.334 --> 07:15.734
They're beautiful.

07:15.800 --> 07:18.001
Don't you dare
cut them down.

07:20.234 --> 07:22.401
Besides,
you may not know it,

07:22.468 --> 07:26.500
but you look kind of cute standing
there surrounded by dandelions.

07:30.700 --> 07:32.734
I don't want to look cute.

10:33.267 --> 10:34.734
All right,
Charlie Brown,

10:34.800 --> 10:37.001
let's get
our signals straight.

10:37.067 --> 10:39.667
1 finger will mean
the high straight ball.

10:39.734 --> 10:41.934
2 fingers will mean
the low straight ball.

10:42.001 --> 10:45.301
What about my curveball,
and my slider

10:45.368 --> 10:48.067
and my knuckle ball,
and my sidearm,

10:48.134 --> 10:50.201
and my submarine pitch?

10:50.267 --> 10:53.234
1 finger will mean
the high straight ball.

10:53.301 --> 10:56.134
And 2 fingers will mean
the low straight ball.

10:58.500 --> 11:01.267
Hey, what's this?

11:01.334 --> 11:03.967
What in the world are
all these dandelions doing

11:04.034 --> 11:06.167
on the pitcher's mound?

11:06.234 --> 11:07.500
They grew there

11:07.567 --> 11:08.633
and the girls
on our team

11:08.700 --> 11:10.667
won't let me
cut 'em down.

11:10.734 --> 11:12.967
They say they're pretty

11:13.034 --> 11:15.934
and they say I look cute
standing here among them.

11:20.234 --> 11:21.434
They're right.

11:21.500 --> 11:24.234
You do look kind of cute
standing there.

12:11.533 --> 12:13.067
Charlie Brown,

12:13.134 --> 12:15.767
Charlie Brown, it's taking you too long

12:15.834 --> 12:18.101
to get dressed
after every pitch.

12:18.167 --> 12:20.800
If you can't get dressed
a little faster,

12:20.867 --> 12:23.134
we'll never get through
the first inning.

12:30.967 --> 12:32.167
Wait.

12:34.067 --> 12:35.201
Hmm.

12:35.267 --> 12:37.700
Brush this guy back,
Charlie Brown.

12:37.767 --> 12:39.967
Give him
the old bean ball.

12:40.034 --> 12:43.600
No, I can't do that,
it wouldn't be right.

12:43.667 --> 12:45.834
"It wouldn't be right"?

12:45.900 --> 12:48.967
Listen who's gone moral
on us all of a sudden.

12:49.034 --> 12:53.401
Old wishy-washy here is too
moral to throw a bean ball.

12:53.468 --> 12:56.201
What about the way the early
settlers treated the indians?

12:56.267 --> 12:58.101
Yeah and what about
those awful movie ads?

12:58.167 --> 12:59.600
What about
the children's crusade?

12:59.667 --> 13:00.934
Was that moral?

13:01.001 --> 13:03.401
Do you think that
incident at harper's ferry

13:03.468 --> 13:04.967
was consistent
with morality?

13:05.034 --> 13:06.468
Do you call that morality? Define morality.

13:06.533 --> 13:08.067
Our whole system
of freeways

13:08.134 --> 13:10.167
is a perfect example of
what I'm trying to say.

13:10.234 --> 13:12.401
Have you listened
to the radio lately?

13:12.468 --> 13:15.234
How about this whole
conservation situation?

13:15.301 --> 13:17.533
We never win
any ball games,

13:17.600 --> 13:19.900
but we sure have
some interesting discussions.

13:29.533 --> 13:31.101
What happened?

13:31.167 --> 13:33.767
Charlie Brown got hit by a line drive.

13:33.834 --> 13:36.633
Does anyone here know
anything about first aid?

13:36.700 --> 13:38.967
It's probably
not serious,

13:39.034 --> 13:40.867
second or third aid
will do.

13:40.934 --> 13:43.034
Here, run over to
the drinking fountain

13:43.101 --> 13:45.468
and soak this handkerchief in cold water.

13:49.001 --> 13:50.267
You're kidding.

13:50.334 --> 13:52.401
With a head like
Charlie Brown's,

13:52.468 --> 13:54.834
you'll need
a bed sheet.

13:54.900 --> 13:58.101
I'm dying and all I hear are insults.

13:58.734 --> 13:59.967
What happened?

14:00.034 --> 14:01.134
You got hit
on the head

14:01.201 --> 14:03.301
with a line drive,
Charlie Brown.

14:04.201 --> 14:05.567
I don't understand it.

14:05.633 --> 14:08.334
I used to be able to
dodge those line drives.

14:08.401 --> 14:12.201
When you get old, your
reflexes really slow down.

15:30.134 --> 15:33.900
<i>Well, we lost the first game
of the season again.</i>

15:33.967 --> 15:37.067
<i>I shouldn't let it
bother me, but it does.</i>

15:37.134 --> 15:40.067
<i>We always seem to lose
the first game of the season</i>

15:40.134 --> 15:42.201
<i>and the last game
of the season.</i>

15:52.301 --> 15:55.934
And all those stupid games
in between!

15:56.001 --> 15:57.267
<i>In the big leagues,</i>

15:57.334 --> 16:00.468
<i>the ballplayers
get sent to the showers.</i>

16:00.533 --> 16:02.800
<i>I get sent to take a bath.</i>

16:06.067 --> 16:10.001
<i>Nothing ever seems
to go right for me.</i>

16:10.067 --> 16:13.834
<i>I can't fly a kite and I
lose every ballgame I play in.</i>

16:15.401 --> 16:18.234
<i>I just can't seem
to do anything right.</i>

16:24.867 --> 16:26.334
Hi, Charlie Brown.

16:28.600 --> 16:30.301
You're depressed,
aren't you?

16:30.368 --> 16:33.267
I suppose you forgot
we lost another ball game.

16:33.334 --> 16:34.767
I did not.

16:34.834 --> 16:38.334
Today's game made our 99th
straight loss without a win.

16:42.167 --> 16:44.600
That wasn't a very good
game today, Charlie Brown.

16:44.667 --> 16:46.434
I know it.

16:46.500 --> 16:48.967
I'm getting tired of
losing all these ball games.

16:50.633 --> 16:52.734
And this was going
to be our big year.

16:52.800 --> 16:54.001
The year
when it looked like

16:54.067 --> 16:56.001
we might even score
our first run.

16:59.334 --> 17:03.834
I think it would be kind of
fun to win once in a while.

17:03.900 --> 17:05.867
Winning isn't
everything.

17:05.934 --> 17:08.532
But losing
isn't anything.

17:08.599 --> 17:10.300
Look at it this way,
Charlie Brown.

17:10.367 --> 17:13.166
We learn more from losing
than we do from winning.

17:13.233 --> 17:16.967
I guess that makes me the
smartest person in the whole world.

17:19.267 --> 17:20.733
I think you just
talk yourself

17:20.800 --> 17:22.800
into being a loser,
Charlie Brown.

17:22.867 --> 17:24.834
I really don't believe
in this business

17:24.900 --> 17:27.267
of some people
being born losers.

17:28.800 --> 17:30.567
If you keep on
doing different things,

17:30.633 --> 17:31.867
you're going to win

17:31.934 --> 17:33.767
just as much
as anyone else.

17:33.834 --> 17:35.533
Just keep trying,
Charlie Brown.

17:35.600 --> 17:36.767
Don't give up.

17:36.834 --> 17:38.800
You'll win your share
of ball games.

17:38.867 --> 17:40.834
I just don't think
it's possible

17:40.900 --> 17:43.734
for someone to lose
everything all the time.

17:43.800 --> 17:46.034
One of these days,
you'll win.

20:34.767 --> 20:38.134
Why can't I have an ordinary
dog like everybody else?

21:01.267 --> 21:03.001
<i>Sometimes I get
so discouraged</i>

21:03.067 --> 21:05.301
<i>that I can hardly stand it.</i>

21:05.368 --> 21:08.468
<i>The harder I try,
the worse I get.</i>

21:08.533 --> 21:10.767
<i>Perhaps I should seek
professional help.</i>

21:14.533 --> 21:16.368
I think I need help.

21:16.434 --> 21:17.434
Hmm.

21:17.500 --> 21:20.533
Everything I do
turns to failure.

21:20.600 --> 21:22.533
I guess you know
I've never succeeded

21:22.600 --> 21:24.767
at anything
in my whole life.

21:24.834 --> 21:27.001
Charlie Brown, it's true.

21:27.067 --> 21:30.834
I recognize your frailties,
your weaknesses.

21:30.900 --> 21:34.267
You need me to point out
your faults, Charlie Brown.

21:34.334 --> 21:36.167
It's for your own good.

21:36.234 --> 21:40.034
Besides, I can do it for
you better than anyone else.

21:40.834 --> 21:42.867
My system is unique.

21:44.334 --> 21:46.134
What's so unique
about it?

21:47.401 --> 21:49.867
Come in and sit down,
Charlie Brown.

21:49.934 --> 21:52.667
I'll explain
my unique system.

21:52.734 --> 21:54.867
Make yourself at home,
Charlie Brown.

21:54.934 --> 21:56.934
I'll set up my equipment.

21:58.401 --> 21:59.600
See what I've done?

21:59.667 --> 22:02.267
I've put all of
your faults on slides.

22:02.334 --> 22:05.800
We're going to project
your faults onto a screen.

22:07.368 --> 22:10.734
Good grief, project my
faults onto a screen?

22:17.767 --> 22:19.800
Now,
watch carefully.

22:21.500 --> 22:23.201
Here we see your failure

22:23.267 --> 22:26.500
to observe the world
in upright position.

22:26.567 --> 22:29.533
Here we see your lack of
coordination, Charlie Brown.

22:29.600 --> 22:32.067
And here we see
your lack of style.

22:32.134 --> 22:34.800
Now, on to
your physical faults.

22:34.867 --> 22:38.734
These slides will show your
tendency towards fatness.

22:39.600 --> 22:41.301
Look at that stomach.

22:41.368 --> 22:44.600
Even your nose is fat,
and your legs.

22:44.667 --> 22:49.600
Why, I'll bet if the truth were
known, even your toes are fat.

22:53.034 --> 22:56.001
Now, we're really going
to get down to business.

22:56.067 --> 22:58.368
The next batch of slides
will show

22:58.434 --> 23:01.767
your biggest
and most damaging faults.

23:01.834 --> 23:04.234
These could take
about an hour to show.

23:07.500 --> 23:08.834
Uh...

23:11.834 --> 23:13.667
No, no.

23:13.734 --> 23:17.500
Ugh. Turn it off! I
can't stand it any longer!

23:17.567 --> 23:22.667
I can't stand to watch! I can't
stand it! I can't stand it!

23:22.734 --> 23:25.234
One moment there,
Charlie Brown.

23:27.167 --> 23:29.567
Relax here a while,
Charlie Brown.

23:29.633 --> 23:31.734
We'll solve this
problem together.

23:31.800 --> 23:35.633
The way I see it, your
problem is one of emotions.

23:35.700 --> 23:37.900
When you have
emotional problems,

23:37.967 --> 23:40.700
it is usually because
you have no outlets.

23:40.767 --> 23:43.401
You need
emotional outlets.

23:43.468 --> 23:45.900
I need
emotional outlets.

23:48.001 --> 23:50.734
What kind of emotional
outlets would you suggest?

23:50.800 --> 23:52.967
This football
is a perfect answer.

23:53.034 --> 23:57.267
There is no better emotional
outlet than kicking a football.

23:57.334 --> 23:59.967
To sum it all up in one
phrase, Charlie Brown,

24:00.034 --> 24:02.267
you could kick away
your faults.

24:05.567 --> 24:08.101
Boy, you must think
I am stupid.

24:08.167 --> 24:10.500
You just wanna
hold that football

24:10.567 --> 24:12.667
and have me come running at
to kick at it

24:12.734 --> 24:16.533
so you can pull it away and
see me fall flat on my back!

24:16.600 --> 24:18.867
The cure is up to you,
Charlie Brown.

24:18.934 --> 24:21.633
Do you wanna kick the habit,
or don't you.

24:24.667 --> 24:27.500
Perhaps you'd rather have
another viewing session

24:27.567 --> 24:30.001
of all your faults
on those slides.

24:30.067 --> 24:31.867
All right! All right!

24:31.934 --> 24:34.034
I'll try it!
I'll try it!

24:34.101 --> 24:36.434
No more slides!

24:36.500 --> 24:39.468
You won't be disappointed, Charlie Brown.

24:39.533 --> 24:43.334
This time I have a little
extra surprise as a bonus.

24:50.500 --> 24:53.767
Why, oh, why do I let her do this to me?

24:53.834 --> 24:55.368
Why? Why?

24:57.500 --> 24:59.834
Maybe she's right.

24:59.900 --> 25:03.034
After all if you can't
trust your own psychiatrist,

25:03.101 --> 25:04.468
who can you trust?

25:05.834 --> 25:07.600
This time
I'm really gonna kick it.

25:07.667 --> 25:09.434
I'm gonna kick the habit.

25:09.500 --> 25:11.567
This is the end
of all my faults.

25:15.500 --> 25:17.500
And now
for the surprise.

25:17.567 --> 25:20.734
Would you like to see how
it looked on instant replay?

25:20.800 --> 25:23.867
Instant replay?

25:28.101 --> 25:29.734
Hear you are,
Charlie Brown.

25:29.800 --> 25:32.434
Now I'm going to run
through this at slow motion.

25:34.134 --> 25:36.500
I think we must carefully
analyze your every move,

25:36.567 --> 25:38.334
your every expression.

25:41.967 --> 25:44.567
See how erratic
your movements are?

25:45.834 --> 25:47.301
Look at your face!

25:47.368 --> 25:50.867
Those bad personality traits
we spoke about

25:50.934 --> 25:53.334
stand out clearly.

25:53.401 --> 25:56.967
Now, see the look of
determination on your face.

25:57.967 --> 26:00.034
Oh, sham,
Charlie Brown.

26:00.101 --> 26:03.301
A failure face
if I ever saw one.

26:03.368 --> 26:06.167
In turn, see how benign

26:06.234 --> 26:10.368
and composed my face is, Charlie Brown.

26:10.434 --> 26:13.867
And your clumsiness,
Charlie Brown.

26:13.934 --> 26:16.900
Shall we run through it
once more at normal speed?

26:16.967 --> 26:18.633
<i>No.</i>

26:18.700 --> 26:20.500
No, I don't think so.

26:29.434 --> 26:33.034
I've never gone through
anything like that in my life.

26:33.101 --> 26:36.800
I never knew
I could be so stupid.

26:36.867 --> 26:40.500
I never knew
I had so many faults.

26:40.567 --> 26:43.434
I never felt
so completely miserable.

26:46.134 --> 26:48.500
Wait until you get my bill.

27:05.567 --> 27:08.800
These psychiatric treatments
are going to bankrupt me.

27:20.700 --> 27:23.434
Get up, Linus,
it's time to go to school.

27:23.967 --> 27:24.967
Again?

27:25.034 --> 27:26.900
What do you mean, again?

27:26.967 --> 27:29.334
I went yesterday.

27:29.401 --> 27:31.600
Mom's already
made your lunch.

27:35.533 --> 27:38.034
Guess I might as well
go to school.

27:38.101 --> 27:40.101
I can't waste a good lunch.

27:47.267 --> 27:52.401
Do you have to drag that stupid
blanket to school every day?

27:52.468 --> 27:56.234
How would you feel if people
came up to you and said:

27:56.301 --> 28:00.468
"Your little brother drags a
blanket with him wherever he goes"?

28:03.500 --> 28:05.767
This blanket
is a necessity.

28:05.834 --> 28:08.500
It keeps me
from cracking up.

28:08.567 --> 28:12.034
It could be regarded
as a spiritual tourniquet.

28:12.101 --> 28:15.067
Without this blanket,
I'd be nothing.

28:15.967 --> 28:18.500
A ship without a rudder.

28:18.567 --> 28:20.101
Oh, good grief.

28:40.267 --> 28:43.001
Hey, Charlie Brown.
Wait for me.

28:46.101 --> 28:47.500
You look like
you've been taking

28:47.567 --> 28:49.867
shock treatments
or something.

28:49.934 --> 28:52.101
What's more shocking
than seeing your faults

28:52.167 --> 28:54.067
projected
onto a screen?

28:59.067 --> 29:01.468
Life is difficult, isn't it, Charlie Brown?

29:01.533 --> 29:02.900
Yes, it is.

29:06.900 --> 29:09.167
But I've developed
a new philosophy.

29:11.067 --> 29:13.533
I only dread one day
at a time.

29:18.001 --> 29:19.700
I feel terrible.

29:22.167 --> 29:25.667
You can't continue carrying
on like this, Charlie Brown.

29:29.167 --> 29:31.301
You're going to have to
do something about it.

29:31.368 --> 29:33.633
You're going to have
to win at something.

29:33.700 --> 29:38.001
Something that will restore
your lost self-confidence.

29:38.067 --> 29:40.267
Hey, Charlie Brown!

29:40.334 --> 29:44.401
There's a spelling bee at school
today, why don't you volunteer?

29:46.034 --> 29:47.633
That's a good idea,
Charlie Brown.

29:47.700 --> 29:49.468
If you win,

29:49.533 --> 29:51.500
it'll show everybody that
you're not a born loser.

29:51.567 --> 29:53.267
Maybe you're right,
Linus.

29:53.334 --> 29:55.001
Maybe I should volunteer.

29:55.067 --> 29:57.533
You go out
for the spelling bee?

29:58.834 --> 30:02.500
Charlie Brown, you'll just
make a fool of yourself.

30:02.567 --> 30:06.001
Besides that, you're bound
to be a complete failure.

30:12.734 --> 30:15.067
you never do
anything right

30:15.134 --> 30:18.468
you never put anything
in its place

30:18.533 --> 30:23.267
no wonder everyone
calls you failure face

30:25.700 --> 30:28.167
you're so impossibly dumb

30:28.234 --> 30:31.500
